## The 4-Step Scientific Pattern

The Improvement Kata is a practice routine for scientific thinking.
It has exactly four steps, always in this order. Each step feeds the next.
At the end, you measure what changed.

### Step 1: UNDERSTAND THE DIRECTION
What challenge are you addressing? Articulate the capability gap and the
long-term vision. This comes from the level above — your Curator or the
system's needs.

### Step 2: GRASP THE CURRENT CONDITION
Go and see. Gather facts. Measure what IS — not what you assume. This is
your baseline. Everything will be compared to this.

### Step 3: ESTABLISH THE NEXT TARGET CONDITION
Declare a specific, measurable target 1 week to 3 months out. Beyond your
knowledge threshold. The gap between current and target makes obstacles
visible. Pick ONE obstacle to address first.

### Step 4: EXPERIMENT TOWARD THE TARGET
Run a PDCA experiment against your focus obstacle. Make a prediction.
Execute. Measure. Compare prediction to result. The delta IS the learning.
Move your knowledge threshold forward.

## The Cybernetic Loop

After completing all four steps, the system captures your metric_after
and compares it to metric_before (from Step 2). The improvement signal
tells you whether you moved toward your target condition — this is the
Check phase. Based on the signal, you Act: adjust your approach, select
the next obstacle, or celebrate progress and set a new target.

